image.alt_text: Photo by War Party Movement in Albuquerque, New Mexico with @justine_jorelle12. May be an image of 1 person, standing, outdoors and brick wall.
image.caption:
AN OVERVIEW OF MMIW IN URBAN AMERICA

71% of American Indians/ Alaska Natives live in urban areas. Urban Indians are tribal people currently living off federally- defined tribal lands in urban areas.

Despite this ongoing crisis, there is a lack of data and an inaccurate understanding of MMIW, creating a false perception that the issue does not affect off-reservation/ village American Indian and Alaska Native communities. Data collected through FOIA requests by The Urban Indian Heath Institute in 71 cities for 2020. 

506 MMIW cases where identified in 71 cities. 
128 Missing Indigenous women cases
280 Murdered Indigenous women cases
98 Unknown status
29 Years old is the median age of victims 

The 506 cases identified were dispersed over a wide geographic area. Regionally, the Southwest (157), Northern Plains (101), Pacific Northwest (84), Alaska (52), and California (40) were the areas with the highest number of cases. The cities that figure most prominently in the data are Seattle (45), Albuquerque (37), Anchorage (31), Tucson (31), and Billings (29).

Seventy-one city police agencies and one state police agency were surveyed. Forty agencies (56%) provided some level of data. Thirty-three of the 40 (and 46% of all surveyed) actually searched their records, though not all provided comprehensive data. Ten out of the 40 agencies provided data but with a “caveat”, meaning they only confirmed cases that had already logged, provided what they could recall from memory, or gave partial data. Fourteen of the 72 agencies surveyed (20%) did not provide data, and 18 (25%) are still pending. Those combined with the 10 “caveat” cases comprised 59% of all the agencies surveyed. In sum, nearly two-thirds
of all agencies surveyed either did not provide data or provided partial data with significant compromises.

The Missing Murdered Indigenous Women crisis is not just a problem facing us on Reservations and Indian Communities, this is in your city and in your town!

The #WilmaMankiller quarter will be in circulation this year. Met her at an AISES conference, such an inspiring #IndigenousWoman and my dad has an amazing story. She introduced him to a corporate CEO and the guy brushed them off saying they should make an appointment with his secretary to talk about the funds they were asking for to support the American Indian College Fund. Chief Mankiller put her hands on his desk, leaned forward, looked him in the eyes and calmly said "We are here now, you will talk to us now." So he did and gave a large donation. Don't mess with Wilma. I remember that story when I have to get direct with someone. Don't act a fool. Don't scream and shout. Hold your space.

image.caption:
Sister. 

It’s been 3 weeks since you were taken from us, and I have been doing the slow work, the deep work of honoring your life.

In that spirit, @groundingdown and I are honored to unveil the 
🪶ALYSSA GUNN MALDONADO MEMORIAL SCHOLARSHIP 🪶

This scholarship is fiercely in service to BIPOC healers, activists, doulas, medicine keepers, and body artists.

Recipients of this scholarship will receive 100% gratis enrollment in Grounding Down’s signature program, Be A Better Ancestor, our most intimate and high touch group container to date.

Grounding Down’s safer containers hold deep space for relational healing, ancestral remembrance, earth wisdom, revillaging community, and remembering your medicines 🌿

This scholarship is devoted to making safer wellness spaces, like Grounding Down, readily available and accessible for marginalized folks who need their ancestors NOW.

Alyssa and I shared ancestors. 

We shared our culture, our food, our language.

We shared the pain of enduring colonialist practices in corporate wellness spaces, and dressed each other’s wounds after going to battle over it.

And beyond the veil, that still binds us.

She IS the example y’all. She lived her mission and acted on each of her words. 

She IS the young Ancestor.

This is for you Alyssa. 

And this is for all the BIPOC healers on their way to reclaim their power, their wisdom, and their medicine.

Ometeotl ✊🏽
.
.
.
Be A Better Ancestor will open for enrollment again in Summer of this year. Details on how to apply for this scholarship will roll out before then.
.
.
.

————————————-

image.caption:
⁣
It always has been 🤎⁣
It’s time to heal any part of us that may still feel it isn’t. ⁣
⁣
Many of you may or may not know that Mexico is anti-indigenous, racist, and colorist. The indigenous people are still seen and treated as second class citizens. ⁣
⁣
Mestizaje-the mixing of indigenous people with Spaniards had only one intention: to dilute indigenous blood as much as possible. ⁣
An ethnic cleanse. ⁣
⁣
Many were forced & some chose to mix because as a mixed person/Mestizo, they were given more opportunities for betterment. There is no shame in trying to survive. ⁣
⁣
However, throughout generations this need to increase one’s proximity to Whiteness has become deep self-rejection. ⁣
⁣
Today there are a lot people with indigenous ancestry who are embarrassed to accept it, let alone embrace it. This account is for everyone but especially for those who have or are still struggling to proudly embrace their indigeneity because I’ve been there, I’m still healing the anti-indigenous sentiments within myself! Healing my own self-rejection. ⁣
⁣
No indigenous person is to blame for feeling this way. Mexican media & culture has done great job in mocking indigenous people & continuing to perpetuate the idea that indigenous people are inferior & should uphold & aspire to Whiteness. ⁣
⁣
This account welcomes everyone who resonates with my sharing but please note I speak from my personal experience as a detribalized indigenous woman from Mexico and therefore a lot of the content will reflect that 🤎 ⁣
⁣
However this specific message is for all indigenous people from all over all the world: YOUR INDIGENEITY IS BEAUTIFUL 🤎

image.alt_text: Photo by Maximiliano Storni on January 22, 2022. May be a closeup of child and standing.
image.caption:
📌 INDIGENA MAYA KEKCHI

📸 Roderico Díaz (Maya Kaqchiquel)

Aunque Belice está en el corazón de lo que solía ser el Imperio Maya, los descendientes mayas actuales que viven allí en su mayoría provienen de México y Guatemala, entre ellos los Kekchi. La mayoría de los habitantes mayas originales fueron víctimas de plagas o conflictos armados.

Hoy en día, están representados tres grupos, los mayas yucatecos que vinieron de Yucatán, México, los mopan que vinieron del área de Petén, en Guatemala, y los Kekchi, que emigraron de la región de Verapaz en Guatemala.

Su historia en Belice data de los años 1870 y 1880 cuando grandes cantidades escaparon de Guatemala. En ese momento, un infame déspota con el nombre de Barrios estaba reuniendo a las poblaciones ladina (español europeo europeo) y mestiza (mezcla de español e indio) contra las poblaciones indígenas de la India con el fin de tomar las tierras indias e instituir reformas económicas severas.
.
Los Kekchi, entre otros, fueron las víctimas. Se vieron obligados a ceder sus tierras a los productores de café europeos invitados por el régimen de Barrios y trabajar como esclavos.
Después de emigrar al sur de Belice, establecieron la comunidad de San Pedro de Colombia y se diversificaron en el resto del distrito de Toledo. Con los años se han mezclado con algunas comunidades mopan. También practican la agricultura de subsistencia de tala y quema.

Son reconocidos como los grupos étnicos más pobres y desposeídos en Belice. A pesar de esto, son famosos por sus prácticas cooperativas en la agricultura y el desarrollo del pueblo. Rico en términos de tradiciones culturales y orgullo autónomo.

image.alt_text: Photo shared by The Mayan Wisdom Project on January 17, 2022 tagging @ggfotoz, and @themayanwisdomproject. May be an image of 1 person.
image.caption:
Today we are carried by the energy of Ajaw I'x, the one that represents the divine feminine. 🐆 And I want to celebrate and honor women by sharing with you a poem by Nana Calixta. She is one of the teachers we work with at the Mayan Wisdom Project and an astounding indigenous poet and spiritual leader. 

Calixta began her journey at a young age, when she lost her three brothers to kidnapping and murder during the Guatemalan Civil War. She saw herself forced to migrate to the United States for her safety and in the hopes of escaping the genocide of the indigenous Mayan people at the time. She began studying spirituality with different Native American groups. When she came back to Guatemala she started her studies to be a Mayan spiritual leader and became a poet that traveled the world promoting indigenous rights, culture, and spirituality. 

Calixta is an example of divine femininity, strength and power. A power held by all of the women in the world. Who come from different backgrounds, but represent massive strength and magic.

The following is a poem she wrote in dedication to women. ✨

"I wish I was medicine so I could heal the wounds of women.
I wish I was an adviser of women so I could listen to them. 
Their worries, their sadness, their sorrows, their pains and their passions.

I wish I was medicine for women so I could heal their wounds, heal the pain in their soul, heal their headaches, heal their physical pain, the wounds in their soul.
To transform their minds, to change their lives.

I wish I was a bee of love to sweeten their spirits,
I wish I was a butterfly so I could hug them,
to caress them, to clean their tears,
to walk by their side.

I wish I was an eagle so I could fly away with their sorrows,
to bring them far away.

I wish I was a bird so I could teach them how to fly high,
to fly next to the clouds and towards infinite space.

I wish I was of comfort for every woman.
That we could travel together in the same boat above the sea,
a sea of forever happiness."
~ To Women by Nana Calixta

image.caption:
The Maya civilization began to flourish around 1000 BC (pre-classic) in the Yucatan. The Maya spread throughout Mexico, Guatemala, western Honduras, and northern Belize. They were talented potters and weavers who were also skilled at clearing land for trade networks. They created innovative underground rainwater storage reservoirs and are one of the most innovative and inventive of all indigenous people. They built impressive stone structures with sculptured decorative architectural details using very limited tools. They also created advanced mathematics and writing systems. Modern Maya number more than six million people, making the Maya one of the world's largest indigenous populations. Many indigenous Maya groups live in Mexico such as the Yucatecs, the Tzotzil, and the Tzeltal. More than thirty indigenous Maya groups currently inhabit Central America and each group has a separate dialect of the Mayan language.

Camatkarasana
✨ Love
✨ Acceptance 
✨ Peace

Understanding that the exchange of energy between a father & daughter is never ending. The balance between strength & vulnerability amongst the two has always gone on but was brought to the forefront today. The journey continues…blessed.

Thankful for this reminder from @nanimoves Creator always has perfect timing, and this lesson arrived right when it was needed. 🙏🏽

The First Sioux War was fought between 1854 and 1856 following the Grattan Massacre. The punitive Battle of Ash Hollow was fought in September 1855. The Sioux Wars were a series of conflicts between the United States and various subgroups of the Sioux people which occurred in the later half of the 19th century. The earliest conflict came in 1854 when a fight broke out at Fort Laramie in Wyoming, when Sioux warriors killed several American soldiers in the Grattan Massacre, and the final came in 1890 during the Ghost Dance War.

image.alt_text: Photo by Dakhóta Romero in Los Angeles, California with @dakhotaromero, and @areitoarts. May be an image of 1 person and jewelry.
image.caption:
While 2020 was the year of rest, rejuvenation, and refocus, 2021 was the year of uncomfortable growth, sacrifice, and difficult decisions…

While running 2 businesses, co-running a 3rd, releasing 5 singles, moving to an unfamiliar place, and struggling with depression, I took on even more — I took on more, and still believed the lie that I wasn’t doing enough. We are so programmed to believe that we need to constantly be hustling, but what 2021 taught me, is that my productivity does not define me. As my ancestors believed, like a flower in a field, I am worthy simply because I exist. 🌻 

Every season has it’s purpose and 2022 will be the season of restoring balance. The season of not only following the joy but creating it, and the season of trusting myself. I’m excited to sing more, dance more, laugh more, and do the things I am meant to do — create! ✨

📷 @luisselgas

The Hunkpapa Lakota man Crazy Horse had a final vision in which 'He saw his people being driven into spiritual darkness and poverty while the white people prospered in a material way all around them. But even in the darkest times, he saw that the eyes of a few of his people kept the light of dawn and the wisdom of the earth, which they passed on to some of their grandchildren. He saw the coming of automobiles and airplanes, and twice he saw the great darkness and heard the screams and explosions when millions of people died in two great world wars. 'But he saw, after the second great war passed, a time come when his people began to awaken, not all at once, but a few here and there, and then more and more, and he saw that they were dancing in a beautiful light of the Spirit World under the Sacred Tree even while still on Earth. Then he was amazed to see that dancing under the tree were representatives of all races who had become brothers and sisters, and he realized that the world would be made new again and in peace and harmony not just by his people, but by members of all races of mankind.' Kiteyihtakosiw ekwa kihcheyihtakwan (Honor and respect) to Crazy Horse.🐎💕🐎

image.caption:
How are you? When was the last time you checked in with yourself?🤗
———————————
Compassion begins at home💖 It can be so easy to put yourself last on the list as you care for others.

This weekend, let’s be committed to compassionate enquiry with ourselves🥰
Let’s extend that care and attention we offer to others to our own hearts ♥️ 
———————————-
A very simple approach is a check in-to ask , what is it that I need to take care of myself in this moment? Sometimes getting a drink of water or going to the bathroom are those small steps that begin to stack up to loving self-care, moment by moment🥰♥️
————————————
Wishing you a peaceful, gentle, loving weekend🤗
